WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.680
Thank you, everyone, for coming. We're really excited to be speaking here today. My name's

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:13.000
Mike Stackhouse, I'm the Chief Innovation Officer of Atorus Research, and with me I

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.260
have Jessica Higgins, Director of Analytics Engineering. But really, I'm a nerd who likes

00:00:17.260 --> 00:00:21.940
to code, and Jessica is a nerd who likes science and coding. Today we're going to be talking

00:00:21.940 --> 00:00:29.760
about our package, our R package, Tplyr. And where I want to start with this is a little

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:34.400
bit about why we made it, because typically I'm speaking at industry conferences that

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:40.080
are pharma-centric, and specifically our pocket of pharma that we work in, which is late-phase

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:46.639
clinical trials. So the first thing to understand about programming for late-phase is that we're

00:00:46.639 --> 00:00:51.400
not doing as much exploratory work, which is what a lot of the tools in the R ecosystem

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:57.520
is built for, allowing you to explore your data, model, and do all sorts of things. But

00:00:57.639 --> 00:01:01.400
when you're in late-phase, a lot of what you need to do is already laid out for you. It's

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:06.919
highly standardized, you already have basically all of the outputs that you need to create,

00:01:06.919 --> 00:01:11.879
so you're really trying to operate more like a factory. So the first kind of principle

00:01:11.879 --> 00:01:16.239
of why we made Tplyr is that summary tables are highly repetitive, so your code should

00:01:16.239 --> 00:01:21.720
be highly reusable. You want to operate like a factory, you're putting out maybe 300 tables

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:25.959
for a single trial. So you need to get through that volume and you need to get through it

00:01:25.959 --> 00:01:31.959
quickly, so you really want to be able to reuse that code. The second principle is that

00:01:31.959 --> 00:01:37.000
actually for the outputs that we create, summarizing the data isn't what takes a lot of time. It's

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:42.279
easy enough to pop a variable into counts or summarize and do some means and standard

00:01:42.279 --> 00:01:45.919
deviations and get those numbers. That doesn't take much time. The cosmetics of getting it

00:01:45.919 --> 00:01:50.839
to look the way that your statistician asks you to is what takes a lot of time. So the

00:01:50.839 --> 00:01:55.320
other thing that we tried to build into the package is that text formatting of numbers

00:01:55.320 --> 00:02:00.099
can be very tedious, so we wanted to make it intuitive and easy. But this package has

00:02:00.099 --> 00:02:04.519
been out for two years at this point, and I've talked about this enough that my team

00:02:04.519 --> 00:02:10.360
is definitely sick about hearing it. So the new thing that is the last principle of what

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:17.119
we've finally gotten there with is that we want to make Tplyr more friendly for interactive

00:02:17.119 --> 00:02:23.360
tables. So back in 2020, we work with a lot of different SAS programming groups who are

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:29.759
looking to adopt R, and the question that I get constantly is why R? And the point that

00:02:29.759 --> 00:02:34.360
was made to me early on that resonated that I've never really forgotten is that someone

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:39.279
told me that the cost of doing an additional, say, adverse event table for a trial within

00:02:39.279 --> 00:02:44.559
their company is free, because you just pop it into a SAS macro and out comes the table

00:02:44.559 --> 00:02:48.919
and you're done. And when you're trying to talk about cost savings and what R can do

00:02:48.919 --> 00:02:54.679
for you in that area, that's a hard thing to compete against when the output is free.

00:02:54.679 --> 00:02:59.559
So what does R really have to offer? And that gets into the world of R Markdown and Shiny

00:02:59.559 --> 00:03:05.000
and interactivity, and that's where we really want to make things more accessible.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.839
So just to give a little bit of background on the package itself, Tplyr, it's an R package

00:03:09.839 --> 00:03:16.759
that we released back in 2020, and I shamelessly took the name from dplyr and the principle

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:23.240
of dplyr that it's a package, a grammar of clinical summary tables.

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:29.160
So the reason that we try to make it a grammar of summary tables is that we wanted to take

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:33.440
your focus off of doing the actual summary and thinking about the algorithms that you

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:37.600
need to write to do the summarization and how you get the numbers that you want and

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:43.639
really design it more based off of describing the output that you want to create. So shifting

00:03:43.639 --> 00:03:49.440
that focus of just saying, this is what I want to build. A statistician, typically you

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:55.240
get your CSR and you get the mocks of the tables that you need to produce, and that's

00:03:55.240 --> 00:03:58.679
going to have different characteristics that are going to need to be fulfilled. So we wanted

00:03:58.679 --> 00:04:04.039
Tplyr syntax to focus on describing the output and building up the characteristics and then

00:04:04.039 --> 00:04:09.279
saying go and build this for me. The last thing was that we also wanted to

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:14.360
really draw our line in the sand. I did not want to anchor into any specific reporting

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:20.359
package itself. I favored Huxtable early on because it had good RTF support. GT has been

00:04:20.359 --> 00:04:26.519
building up over the last few years and it's had an amazing place. Jessica loves FlexTable.

00:04:26.519 --> 00:04:30.519
And then in the Shiny world, you have things like Reactable. So I wanted to make the things

00:04:30.519 --> 00:04:36.920
that come out of our package really easily accessible to any styling package that you

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:40.640
want to create. And we just wanted to really stop at the character formatting and the numbers

00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:44.359
so that that annoying part was done for you and that you can pop it into some other library

00:04:44.359 --> 00:04:50.160
that will actually make it pretty. I've never been good at that. That's why I hired Maya.

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:56.679
So to describe Tplyr itself, I want to thank Christina Fillmore for giving me the best

00:04:56.679 --> 00:05:01.920
metaphor for this that I've had, which is think about cake. So cake can take a lot of

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:05.679
forms. It can have a lot of flavors and it can have a lot of different decorations. You

00:05:05.679 --> 00:05:09.679
can have multiple layers into your cake and those things can look differently depending

00:05:09.679 --> 00:05:14.720
on how you build it up. And that's really what a Tplyr table ends up being. So for a

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:20.399
demographics table, which I have a concise example of up here, we have three different

00:05:20.399 --> 00:05:24.279
variables from our dataset that are being summarized. So we have the age group of subjects,

00:05:24.279 --> 00:05:29.000
which is a categorical variable. We have age, which is a continuous variable. And then we

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.720
have race, which is another categorical variable. So for the categorical variables, you're going

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:37.760
to count. You're going to represent percents. And then for the continuous variables, you're

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:42.200
going to do different descriptive statistics for your end mean, standard deviation, so

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:46.480
on and so forth. And then those things are all going to be combined together and they're

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:50.359
going to have their different characteristics of how you want that styled. And we're going

00:05:50.359 --> 00:05:55.239
to bake our cake and pop that out and you get the data frame all collected together

00:05:55.239 --> 00:06:00.000
and assembled and ready formatted so that you can go and put that into some sort of

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:07.600
presentation. But our focus here today and what we're talking about for Tplyr today is

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:11.880
what metadata can really bring to the table. So the question that we're trying to answer

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:17.200
and what we're trying to make accessible here is that when you look at a result on the table,

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:20.600
asking the question, what data produced that result? So if I look at this table, I know

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:25.799
that I have six subjects in the low-dose subgroup who are black or African-American, but who

00:06:25.799 --> 00:06:29.880
are the six subjects? What are the data that were summarized to actually produce that

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:36.839
result? If I'm looking at the median of the high-dose group, again, what data produced

00:06:36.839 --> 00:06:41.720
that result? What subjects were fed in? What was the data that went into my dplyr summarize

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:46.000
and went through the median function to actually produce that result? Because these are questions

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.399
that are often asked when you want to drill down into your data and understand more about

00:06:50.399 --> 00:06:57.359
it. So specifically, when we talk about metadata within Tplyr, we're asking two different questions.

00:06:57.359 --> 00:07:02.320
What variables were necessary to derive that result? And what filters were necessary to

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:06.600
derive that result? So really, what is the slice of data picking out the different columns

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:11.440
and the different rows that were actually necessary to produce the result that you see

00:07:11.440 --> 00:07:16.399
on the table? And here, I will hand it over to Jess.

00:07:16.399 --> 00:07:24.799
Okay. So thanks, Mike, for giving us a great intro on why you created Tplyr, and now we've

00:07:24.799 --> 00:07:33.920
talked about what do we mean by metadata. So how are we going to harness this metadata?

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:40.839
So in this process, you've created your Tplyr table, which produces your summary data frame.

00:07:40.839 --> 00:07:46.920
These are the results you see. You would see them on paper if you printed it out. And additionally,

00:07:46.920 --> 00:07:54.000
what we're doing here now is including this table metadata. That metadata, remember, those

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:59.799
are the names and the variables used to create that result. And we can use that metadata

00:07:59.799 --> 00:08:06.160
to create the relevant subset, and we can wrap all of this in a really easy, shiny application

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:11.119
to create an interactive table that, upon a click action, will give us both our summary

00:08:11.119 --> 00:08:17.459
table and the actual data that produced that result.

00:08:17.459 --> 00:08:23.200
So what does this look like? And building it. So how do you get that metadata? Do you

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:28.720
have to save? It's very simple. So creating the metadata, all you have to do is change

00:08:28.720 --> 00:08:36.479
the argument, metadata equals true, and what will happen is the metadata for this, for

00:08:36.479 --> 00:08:44.400
your table, will just be created automatically. For example, we have our result output data

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:51.039
frame, and now you can see what's actually added to the table is the Tplyr metadata object.

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:57.159
So each cell contains this object, and this object is the metadata, again, those variables,

00:08:57.159 --> 00:09:04.599
those names that created that specific result cell. As we were talking about earlier, this

00:09:04.599 --> 00:09:11.479
is indicated by a row ID and a column ID, and we can go from there to find who are these

00:09:11.479 --> 00:09:17.080
people. They're not just numbers in the summary table. These are subjects in a clinical trial.

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:22.359
So we've got this metadata. How do we extract it? What do we see? How do we get to this?

00:09:22.359 --> 00:09:27.239
As I mentioned, the input is really simple. You supply it a Tplyr table, a row ID, and

00:09:27.239 --> 00:09:33.320
a column name, and the output, what I really like about this, is that you can see, okay,

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:37.520
these are the names that are required to create this result. I already know what columns I'm

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:43.840
looking at. These are the filters, and you can see exactly what it looks like. What are

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:50.159
the filters that are going into that result? You're saying, great, I see this. Where the

00:09:50.159 --> 00:09:57.159
heck is that subset? What is this data? This is a really simple function, too. Again, it's

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:04.760
a new function, getMetaSubset. You provide the same inputs, and it produces that subset,

00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:12.520
that subset of data that produced your results. You can see exactly who is in that result.

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:20.520
Additionally, this getMetaSubset function includes an additional argument to add relevant

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:28.200
columns that might give your subset a little additional context. It defaults to uSubjId,

00:10:29.559 --> 00:10:36.559
which is, for those of you in the clinical world, it's a CDISC-specific variable that

00:10:37.559 --> 00:10:42.799
all these datasets have. However, you can change it to whatever you want. This is the

00:10:42.799 --> 00:10:49.799
only place where any clinical or CDISC-specific defaults or language is used in this package.

00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:57.200
We really want tplayer to be extensible beyond just using finished CDISC data, but this is

00:10:57.239 --> 00:11:04.239
the one place where you see it. To summarize, we've created our tplayer table, which includes

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:10.640
our summary results. We've got our relevant metadata, our filters and names. We can create

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:14.679
the subset to see that. What does this actually look like in an interactive table?

00:11:14.679 --> 00:11:21.679
I'm going to give you a quick little demo. What you're going to see is the most bare

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:28.760
bones basic Shiny app ever created. I'm pretty proud of this fact. I didn't create it, but

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:36.200
I could, and I'm not a Shiny developer. Here it is, all its glory. In fact, it's so simple,

00:11:39.159 --> 00:11:44.520
it's 85 lines long, which I had to look up. Again, you can see the code. We'll provide

00:11:44.520 --> 00:11:51.520
that. What do we have here? You can drive around. You want to see, as we mentioned earlier,

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:58.280
we were looking at who are those eight subjects in the placebo group that are black or African

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:05.280
American. You click on the result, and your metadata subset pops up. You can see it. You

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:12.320
can check. This is incredibly useful. As someone who spent a lot of time looking at summary

00:12:13.119 --> 00:12:19.440
tables, then looking at a really long listing, trying to find those people individually,

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:25.000
or programming it on the side while you're comparing at a summary table, to be able to

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:32.000
see all of these things at once, to take your review from a very manual process to something

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:38.479
that's interactive, that's quick, that's fast. That's what we're about, trying to make things

00:12:38.479 --> 00:12:45.479
quicker, faster, and easier, and to bring pharma along in that process slowly.

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:53.320
Okay, that's great. Regular summary table. These are pretty common. What about if you

00:12:57.080 --> 00:13:01.479
are in an example where you have a summary table, and you've included some additional

00:13:01.479 --> 00:13:06.000
statistical analyses or models, and you have those results that you want to share, and

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:10.559
you also want to include the metadata for that test. You want to know exactly what subjects

